| caption1= [[John William Waterhouse|Waterhouse]]: ''Narcissus'', 1912
}}
{{multiple image |header=Narcissi as religious symbols| align = left | direction = vertical | width = 150 | float = none
| image1= WestfaelischerMeister GrosserKalvarienberg WRM 0353 c Rheinisches Bildarchiv-rba c004444.jpg
| caption1= Crucifixion, Westf<U+00E4>lischer Meister c. 1415
| image2=Meisternoli.jpg
| caption2= ''[[Noli me tangere]]'', [[Meister des G<U+00F6>ttinger Barf<U+00FC><U+00DF>eraltars]] c. 1410}}
Although there is no clear evidence that the flower's name derives directly from the Greek myth, this link between the flower and the myth became firmly part of western culture.

The narcissus or daffodil is the most loved of all English plants,{{sfn|Ellacombe|1884|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=autIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA73 Daffofils p. 73]}} and appears frequently in English literature. Many English writers have referred to the cultural and symbolic importance of ''Narcissus'', for instance [[Elizabeth Kent (writer)|Elizabeth Kent]] (''Flora Domestica'', 1823{{sfn|Anonymous|1823)}}), [[FW Burbidge]] (''The Narcissus'', 1875{{sfn|Burbidge|1875}}), Peter Barr (''Ye Narcissus Or Daffodyl Flowere'', 1884{{sfn|Barr|Burbidge|1884}}), and Henry Ellacombe (''The Plant-lore & Garden-craft of Shakespeare'', 1884{{sfn|Ellacombe|1884}}). No flower has received more poetic description except the [[rose]] and the [[lily]], with poems by authors including [[John Gower]], [[Edmund Spenser|Spenser]], [[Henry Constable|Constable]], [[Shakespeare]], [[Joseph Addison|Addison]] and [[James Thomson (poet)|Thomson]], together with Milton (see [[#Roman culture|Roman culture]], above), [[Wordsworth]], [[Percy Bysshe Shelley|Shelley]] and [[Keats]]. Frequently the poems deal with self-love derived from Ovid's account.<ref name=PoetryNarcissus/> An example of this is Gower's retelling of Ovid's ''Metamorphoses'' :{{sfn|Ellacombe|1884|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=autIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA74 Daffofils p. 74]}}
{{Quote|For in the winter fresh and faire<br>The flowres ben, which is contraire<br>To kind, and so was the folie<br>Which fell of his surquedrie<ref group=notes>''Surquederie'': Arrogance, pride; presumptuousness (Middle English Dictionary) {{harv|MED|2013|loc=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/m/mec/med-idx?type=id&id=MED43921&egs=all&egdisplay=open ''Surquederie'']}}</ref>|sign=John Gower|source= [[Confessio Amantis]] 1390 {{sfn|Gower|1390|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=MVQJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA121 Confes. Aman. liber primus The Tale of [[Narcissus (mythology)|Narcissus]] (I.2275<U+2013>2366) ''l.'' 2355]}}<ref group=notes>The original ([[Project Gutenberg]]) reads {{Quote|For in the wynter freysshe and faire<br>The floures ben, which is contraire<br>To kynde, and so was the folie<br>Which fell of his Surquiderie {{Harv|Gower|2008|loc=''l.'' 2355}}}}</ref>}}

Gower's reference to the yellow flower of the legend has been assumed to be the daffodil or ''Narcissus'',  {{sfn|Ellacombe|1884|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=autIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA74 Daffofils p. 74]}} though as with all references in the older literature to the flower that sprang from the youth's death, there is room for some debate as to the exact species of flower indicated, some preferring ''[[Crocus]]''.{{sfn|Yeager|1990|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=SmH4Q4GMyHEC&pg=PA133 Transformations pp. 133<U+2013>135]}}

Spenser announces the coming of the Daffodil in ''Aprill'' of his ''[[Shepheardes Calender]]'' (1579), "Strowe me the ground with Daffadowndillies".{{sfn|Spenser|1579|loc=[http://www.luminarium.org/renascence-editions/aprill.html Aprill ''l.'' 140]}}
Constable compares the object of affection to the daffodil,
{{Quote|DIAPHENIA like the daffadowndilly,<br>White as the sun, fair as the lily,<br>Heigh ho, how I do love thee!|sign=Henry Constable|source=''Diaphenia'' 1600{{sfn|Constable|1600|loc=[https://archive.org/stream/dianasonnetsothe00consuoft#page/66/mode/2up Contributions to England's Helicon. I Diaphenia]}}}}

Shakespeare, [[Shakespeare garden|who frequently uses flower imagery]],{{sfn|Ellacombe|1884}} refers to daffodils twice in ''[[The Winter's Tale]]'' (Autolycus act iv, sc. 3(1) "When Daffodils begin to peer" and Perdita act iv, sc. 4(118) "Daffodils, That come before the swallow dares, and take The winds of March with beauty" 1623).,{{sfn|Shakespeare|1623|loc=Perdita, IV 4}} and also in ''[[The Two Noble Kinsmen]]''  (act iv, sc. 1(94) "chaplets on their heads of Daffodillies" 1634). However Shakespeare also uses the term 'Narcissus' in the latter (act ii, sc. 2(130) "What flowre is this? Tis called Narcissus, madam").{{sfn|Shakespeare|1634|loc=Emilia, II 2 p. 9}}

[[Robert Herrick (poet)|Robert Herrick]], in ''[[Hesperides (poetry)|Hesperides]]'' (1648) alludes to their association with death in a number of poems such as ''To Daffadils'' ("Faire Daffadills we weep to see, You haste away so soone") <ref name=Herrick2/> and ''Divination by a Daffadill'';

{{Quote|When a daffadill I see,<br>Hanging down his head t'wards me,<br>Guesse I may, what I must be:<br>First, I shall decline my head;<br>Secondly, I shall be dead:<br>Lastly, safely buryed|sign=Herrick|source=''Divination by a Daffadill'', ''Hesperides'' 1648<ref name=Herrick1/>}}

Amongst the English [[romantic movement]] writers none is better known than [[William Wordsworth]]'s short 1804 poem ''[[I Wandered Lonely as a Cloud]]'' (The Daffodils)<ref name=WW1/> which has become linked in the popular mind with the daffodils that form its main image,<ref name=Dweck/><ref name=PoetryNarcissus/><ref name=WTrust/> here associated with vitality and pleasure.<ref name=Kandeler/> Wordsworth also included the daffodil in other poems, such as ''Foresight''.<ref name=WW2/> Yet the description given of daffodils by his sister, [[Dorothy Wordsworth|Dorothy]] is just as poetic, if not more so,{{sfn|Ellacombe|1884|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=autIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA76 Daffofils p. 76]}} just that her poetry was prose and appears almost an unconscious imitation of first section of the Homeric ''Hymn to Demeter'' (see [[#Greek culture|Greek culture]], above);{{sfn|LQR|1853|loc=[https://books.google.ca/books?id=SJTfAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA112 Memoirs of Wordsworth, Issue 183, January, p. 112]}}{{sfn|Ellacombe|1884|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=autIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA76 Daffofils p. 76]}}

{{Quote|I never saw daffodils so beautiful they grew among the mossy stones about & about them, some rested their heads upon these stones as on a pillow for weariness & the rest tossed & reeled & danced & seemed as if they verily laughed with the wind that blew upon them over the Lake, they looked so gay ever glancing ever changing|sign=Dorothy Wordsworth|source=''Grasmere Journal'' 15 April 1802{{sfn|Wordsworth|1802}}}}

Amongst their contemporaries, Keats refers to daffodils amongst those things capable of bringing 'joy for ever';

{{Quote|A thing of beauty is a joy for ever:<br>...<br>Some shape of beauty moves away the pall...<br>and such are daffodils, With the green world they live in|sign=Keats|source=''[[Endymion (poem)|Endymion]]'' 1818{{sfn|Keats|1818}}}}

while Shelley looks back to the legend in his description of the flower;

{{Quote|And narcissi, the fairest among them all,<br>Who gaze on their eyes in the stream<U+2019>s recess,<br>Till they die of their own dear loveliness|sign=Shelley|source=''The Sensitive Plant'' 1820{{sfn|Shelley|1820|loc=1. ''l.'' 18}}}}

[[A. E. Housman]], using one of the daffodil's more symbolic names (see [[#Symbols|Symbols]]), wrote the Spring poem ''The Lent Lily'' in his collection ''[[A Shropshire Lad]]'', describing the traditional Easter death of the daffodil:

{{Quote|And there's the Lenten lily,<br> That has not long to stay,<br> And dies on Easter day|sign=Housman|source=''The Lent Lily'', 1896{{sfn|Housman|1896|loc=XXIX ''The Lent Lily'', 1896}}}}

Later [[Cecil Day-Lewis]] wrote:

{{Quote|Now the full throated daffodils,<br> Our trumpeters in gold,<br> Call resurrection from the ground,<br> And bid the year be bold|sign=C Day Lewis|source=''From Feathers to Iron'', 1931{{sfn|Lewis|1992|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=FdFmmsHbsZsC&pg=PA115 ''From Feathers to Iron'' (1931) p. 115]}}}}

In  ''Black Narcissus'' (1939) [[Rumer Godden]] describes the disorientation of English nuns in the Indian [[Himalayas]], and gives the plant name an unexpected twist, alluding both to [[narcissism]] and the effect of the perfume ''Narcisse Noir'' ([[Parfums Caron|Caron]]) on others. The novel was later adapted into the  [[Black Narcissus|1947 British film of the same name]].

The narcissus also appears in German literature. [[Paul Gerhardt]], a pastor and hymn writer wrote:

{{Quote|''Narzissus und die Tulipan''<br>''Die ziehen sich viel sch<U+00F6>ner an''<br>''Als Salomonis Seide''<br>Daffodil and tulip are dressed more beautifully than Solomon's silk|sign=Paul Gerhardt|source=''[[Geh aus, mein Herz, und suche Freud]]'', 1653 (Second verse)<ref name=Gerhardt/>}}

In the visual arts, narcissi are depicted in three different contexts, mythological (Narcissus, Persephone), floral art, or landscapes. The Narcissus story has been popular with painters and the youth is frequently depicted with flowers to indicate this association, for instance those of [[Fran<U+00E7>ois Lemoyne]], [[John William Waterhouse]], and that of [[Poussin]] depicting flowers sprouting around the dying Narcissus,<ref name=Panofsky/> or [[Salvador Dal<U+00ED>]]'s ''[[Metamorphosis of Narcissus]]''.<ref name=SOED/> The Persephone theme is also typified by Waterhouse in his ''Narcissus'', the floral [[motif (visual arts)|motif]] by [[Jan van Scorel|van Scorel]] and the landscape by [[Van Gogh]]'s ''Undergrowth''.

Narcissi first started to appear in western art in the [[late middle ages]], in [[panel paintings]], particularly those depicting [[crucifixion]]. For instance there is a crucifixion scene by the Westf<U+00E4>lischer Meister in K<U+00F6>ln (c. 1415 <U+2013> 1435) in the [[Wallraf-Richartz-Museum]], [[Cologne]],<ref name=Cologne/> where daffodils symbolise not only death but also hope in the [[resurrection]], because they are perennial and bloom at [[Easter]].<ref name=Kandeler/><ref name=resur/> Another example from this period is the [[altarpiece]] panel ''[[Noli me tangere]]'' from the [[Magdalenenkirche, Hildesheim|Magdalenenkirche]], [[Hildesheim]] Germany, by the [[Meister des G<U+00F6>ttinger Barf<U+00FC><U+00DF>eraltars]] (c. 1410).<ref name=Stuttgart/> In the centre of the panel, between the hand of Jesus and [[Mary Magdalene]], daffodils can be seen growing.<ref name=Kandeler/>

==== Eastern cultures ====
{{multiple image |header=Narcissi in Eastern culture| align = left | direction = vertical | width = 150 | float = none
|image2=Shuixiandiaoke.JPG
|caption2=Chinese decorative carved ''Narcissus'' bulb
|image3=Tachikawa Township narcissus 04.JPG
|caption3=Narcissus fields, [[Awaji Island]], Japan
|image1=Narcissus tazetta var chinensis1.jpg
|caption1=Chinese Sacred Lily
}}
In [[Chinese culture]] interest in narcissi centres on ''[[Narcissus tazetta]]'', which can be grown indoors. ''Narcissus tazetta'' subsp. ''chinensis'' is widely grown in China as an ornamental plant<ref name=FOC/> and often known outside China as Chinese sacred lilies (''N. tazetta'' 'Chinese Sacred Lily', <U+6C34><U+4ED9><U+82B1>) or joss flowers.<ref name=Todt/> Tazetta daffodils were probably introduced to China, where they became naturalised, by Arab traders travelling the [[Silk Road]] at some time prior to the beginning of the [[Song Dynasty]] (i.e. before 960), presumably for their claimed medicinal properties.<ref name=Zonneveld/><ref name=FOC/><ref name=Todt/> Flowering in spring, they became associated with [[Chinese New Year]], signifying good fortune, prosperity and good luck. If the narcissus blooms on Chinese New Year, it is said to bring extra wealth and good fortune throughout the year. Its sweet fragrance is also highly revered in Chinese culture. The flower has many names in Chinese culture, including water narcissus (since they can be grown in water) and ''seui sin faa'' (water immortal flowers).<ref name=Todt/> In [[Ancient China|ancient Chinese culture]] the narcissus is referred to as water goddess of the [[Xiang River]] ({{lang-zh|<U+6C34><U+4ED9>, ''shu<U+01D0> xi<U+0101>n''}}), or the "goddess standing above the waves" (''lingbo xianzi''),<ref name=Mengjian/> also translated as "fairy over rippling waters".<ref name=Globaltimes/> There are many legends in Chinese culture associated with ''Narcissus'',{{sfn|Hu|1989}}{{sfn|Bailey|1890}} including one of a poor but good man who was brought great wealth by this flower.{{sfn|Gippsland Times|1946}}

As Chinese Garden Art expert [[Marianne Beuchert]] writes, in contrast to the West, narcissi have not played a significant part in [[Chinese Garden]] art, but have become a symbol of good luck, in which the multi-headed inflorescence of ''N. tazetta'' symbolised a hundred headed water spirit.<ref name="Beuchert"/> However, [[Zhao Mengjian]] (<U+8D99><U+5B5F><U+5805>, c. 1199 <U+2013> 1267), in the [[Culture of the Song Dynasty|Southern Song Dynasty]] was noted for his portrayal of narcissi,{{sfn|Hearn|2008|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=SLpZy5ouhcgC&pg=PA70 Zhao Mengjian p. 70]}} and Zhao's love of the flower is celebrated by the loyalist [[Song poetry|Song poet]] Qiu Yuan (c. 1247 <U+2013> 1327).{{sfn|Hearn|2008|loc=[http://books.google.ca/books?id=SLpZy5ouhcgC&pg=PA70 Zhao Mengjian p. 70 "I pity the narcissus for not being the orchid, which at least had known the sober minister from Chu".]}}

Narcissus bulb carving and cultivation has become an art akin to Japanese [[bonsai]]. The bulbs may be carved to create curling leaves (crab claw culture). The bulbs can produce six to eleven flower stems from a single bulb, each with an average of eight fragrant blooms.<ref name=Hu/> With the additional use of props such as ribbons, artificial eyes, bindings and florists' wire, even more elaborate scenarios can be created, representing traditional subjects such as [[rooster]]s, [[Crane (bird)|cranes]], flower baskets and even teapots.<ref name=Globaltimes/>

The Japanese visual novel ''[[Narcissu]]'' contains many references to the narcissus, the main characters setting out for the famed narcissus fields on [[Awaji Island]], ''N. tazetta'' having also naturalised there.{{sfn|Awaji|2006|loc=[http://www.eonet.ne.jp/~t-suisen/index.html Awaji Tachikawa Narcissus Farmland]}}{{sfn|Awaji|2006|loc=[http://www.city.minamiawaji.hyogo.jp/soshiki/shoukou/suisenkyou.html Nada Kurokawa Narcissus Field]}}

==== Islamic culture ====
{{multiple image| align = left | direction = vertical | width = 150 | float = none
|image1=Narcissus poeticus.jpg
|caption1=''[[Narcissus poeticus|N. poeticus]]'' symbolising the eye in Islamic culture
|image2=Field of Narcissuses - 20070502.jpg
|caption2=Narcissi (May Snow) growing near [[Montreux]] in May
|image3=Marie Curie Cancer Care logo.png}}
Islamic scholar [[Annemarie Schimmel]] states that the narcissi are one of the most popular garden plants in [[Islamic culture]].{{sfn|Schimmel|1998| p=71}} The Persian ruler Chusrau Anuschirwan, or [[Khosrau I]] (531 <U+2013> 579) is said to have not been able to tolerate them at feasts because they reminded him of eyes, an association that persists to this day,<ref name=Schimmel165/> as described by the poet [[Ghalib]] (1797 <U+2013> 1869), "God has given the eye of the narcissus the power of seeing".<ref name=Schimmel165/> The imagery could also be negative, such as blindness (white eye),<ref name=Schimmel165/>  sleepless or longing for love. The eye imagery is also found in a number of poems by [[Abu Nuwas]] (756 <U+2013> 814).{{sfn|Meisami|Starkey|1998| p=545}}{{sfn|Meisami|Starkey|1998| p=583}}{{sfn|Meisami|Starkey|1998| p=662}} In one of his most famous poems about narcissi he writes "eyes of silver with pupils of molten gold united with an emerald stalk".{{sfn|Schimmel|1998| p=72}} Schimmel describes an Arab legend that despite the apparent sinfulness of much of his poetry, his narcissus poems alone would earn him a place in [[Paradise]].{{sfn|Schimmel|1998| p=72}} Another poet who refers to narcissi, is [[Rumi]] (1207 <U+2013> 1273). Even the prophet [[Mohammed]] is said to have praised the narcissus, "Whoever has two loaves of bread, sell one and buy narcissi, for while bread nourishes the body, the narcissus feeds the soul".{{sfn|Krausch|2012| p=379}}

=== Popular culture ===
The word 'Daffodil' has been [[Daffodil (disambiguation)|used widely]] in popular culture from [[DAF Daffodil|Dutch cars]] to [[The Daffodils|Swedish rock bands]].

=== Festivals ===
In some areas where wild narcissi are particularly prevalent, their blooming in spring is celebrated in festivals. The slopes around [[Montreux]], Switzerland and its associated [[riviera]] come alive with blooms each May (''May Snow''), and are associated with the Narcissi Festival. However, the narcissi are now considered threatened.<ref name=Montreux/> Festivals are held in many other countries and regions including [[Canton of Fribourg|Fribourg]] (Switzerland), [[Austria]] and in the [[United States]], including [[Hawaii]] (Chinese New Year) and [[Washington (state)|Washington State]]'s [[The Daffodil Festival|Daffodil Festival]].

=== Cancer ===
Various cancer charities around the world, including  the [[American Cancer Society]],<ref name=ACS/> New Zealand Cancer Society,<ref name=NZCS/> [[Cancer Council Australia]],<ref name=CCA/> the [[Irish Cancer Society]],<ref name=ICS/> and [[Marie Curie Cancer Care|Marie Curie]] (UK)'s [[Great Daffodil Appeal]]<ref name=MCurie/> use the daffodil emblem as a fundraising symbol. "Daffodil Days", first instituted in Toronto in 1957 by the [[Canadian Cancer Society]],<ref name=CCS/> are organized to raise funds by offering the flowers in return for a donation.

